{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 18:36:03.657575", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary\\n- Anomaly detected: The web service for pod0 (web0.pod0 -> 10.0.1.2) is unreachable from anywhere off the host. TCP connections to 10.0.1.2:80 are consistently refused, despite DNS and routing working normally.\\n- Localization: Issue is localized to the service host webserver0_pod0 (10.0.1.2) or its immediate host-level policies. The routed fabric and BGP path are not implicated.\\n- Probable root cause: The HTTP service accepts only local connections; inbound connections from other hosts are actively rejected (TCP RST). This points to a host-level filtering/policy or socket accessibility problem on webserver0_pod0 rather than a network forwarding issue.\\n\\nEvidence and Findings\\n\\n1) Client experience and DNS\\n- Client resolution is correct:\\n  - client_0: getent hosts web0.pod0 -> 10.0.1.2 web0.pod0\\n  - /etc/resolv.conf on client_0 points at pod DNS servers (10.0.0.2 and 10.1.0.2).\\n- DNS servers are up and listening:\\n  - dns_pod0: named service active (running); netstat shows :53 listening on 10.0.0.2 and 127.0.0.1.\\n\\n2) L3 reachability (routing/ICMP)\\n- Ping reachability across the fabric is healthy (no loss, low RTTs):\\n  - client_0 -> webserver0_pod0 (10.0.1.2): OK (avg ~1.1 ms).\\n  - Multiple other source hosts to 10.0.1.2: OK.\\n- This indicates correct routing/BGP advertisement of 10.0.1.0/24 and proper connectivity across super-spine/spine/leaf.\\n\\n3) L4 application connectivity (HTTP)\\n- From client_0 and other hosts, HTTP connection to 10.0.1.2:80 fails with Connection refused:\\n  - client_0: curl http://web0.pod0 and http://10.0.1.2 -> code=000; verbose shows “connect to 10.0.1.2 port 80 failed: Connection refused.”\\n  - dns_pod0, webserver1_pod0, webserver0_pod1, webserver2_pod1: same “Connection refused” to 10.0.1.2:80.\\n  - leaf_router_0_1 (directly connected to the subnet): same refusal (immediate).\\n- On the server itself (webserver0_pod0), HTTP is listening and responds locally:\\n  - netstat shows python3 listening on 0.0.0.0:80 (PID 28/python3).\\n  - Local curl to 127.0.0.1 and to 10.0.1.2 returns HTTP 200.\\n- Host-level packet filters do not show explicit deny rules:\\n  - webserver0_pod0: iptables INPUT/FORWARD/OUTPUT policies ACCEPT; nftables ruleset shows only NAT chains for 127.0.0.11 (Docker DNS stub); no filter chains.\\n  - leaf_router_0_1: iptables ACCEPT; no filter rules rejecting TCP/80.\\n\\nAssessment\\n\\n- Health of underlay and control plane:\\n  - DNS infrastructure is healthy (authoritative and reachable).\\n  - Routing fabric is healthy (ICMP reachability end-to-end is normal).\\n- Health of the web service:\\n  - Process is running and bound to 0.0.0.0:80; local access works.\\n  - However, all non-local TCP connection attempts are met with immediate refusal (RST), including from the directly connected leaf.\\n  - This behavior is inconsistent with a routing or intermediary firewall issue (which would typically cause timeouts/drops), and instead indicates active rejection by the endpoint host for non-local connections.\\n\\nRoot Cause Hypothesis\\n\\n- The webserver host webserver0_pod0 is rejecting inbound TCP connections to port 80 from remote sources while allowing local connections. Given the absence of visible iptables/nftables filter rules and the python server listening on 0.0.0.0:80, the most plausible cause is a host-level policy or configuration specific to inbound external connections to port 80 (e.g., hidden/alternative filtering mechanism, namespace-specific constraints, or service accessibility constraints), not a fabric routing or DNS issue.\\n\\nImpact\\n\\n- External clients (e.g., client_0) cannot access http://web0.pod0 due to TCP connection refusal at the destination host, despite correct name resolution and IP reachability., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='746ce128-63b2-4683-b3f7-95b95f960ae8'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
